04082nam a22005535i 9780774820646DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20112011xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748206467 a10.59962/97807748206462doi  a(DE-B1597)661152  a(OCoLC)779696148  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJC599.C3bD53 2011eb 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a323.1711 aDick, Caroline, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Perils of Identity :bGroup Rights and the Politics of Intragroup Difference /cCaroline Dick. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (260 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tGender Discrimination within First Nations: The History and Nature of the Sawridge Dispute -- tGroup Rights and the Politics of Identity -- tTaylor’s Theory of Identity Recognition -- tKymlicka’s Cultural Theory of Minority Rights -- tEisenberg’s Theory of Identity-Related Interests -- tCulture, Identity, and the Constitutional Rights of Aboriginal Peoples -- tThe Politics of Intragroup Difference -- tSawridge Revisited -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCalls for the provision of group rights are a common part of politics in Canada. Many liberal theorists consider identity claims a necessary condition of equality, but do these claims do more harm than good? To answer this question, Caroline Dick engages in a critical analysis of liberal identity-driven theories and their application in cases such as Sawridge Band v. Canada, which sets a First Nation's right to self-determination against indigenous women's right to equality. She contrasts Charles Taylor's theory of identity recognition, Will Kymlicka's cultural theory of minority rights, and Avigail Eisenberg's theory of identity-related interests with an alternative rights framework that account for both group and in-group differences. Dick concludes that the problem is not the concept of identity itself but the way in which prevailing conceptions of identity and group rights obscure intragroup differences. Instead, she proposes a politics of intragroup difference that has the power to transform rights discourse in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIdentity politics -- Canada. 0aMinorities -- Civil rights -- Canada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077482064640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774820646423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774820646/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles